===subject:Envy of the American people?
===from:Mark Prosper
===date:Mon Dec  9  0:15:46 2002
===message:I don't think that most Soviets envied life in America.  To an extent some Soviet citizens may have.  But when the populous is fed a steady diet of taboo and stigma towards the U.S. and a sense of praise and the hope of better days to come under their current rule, their perception is framed, and any evidence supporting their imposed ideas is magnified.  Trends show that each generation is brought up with a set of beliefs or"theme"which is influenced by the events of their time.  So to those coming up in the communist nation, nothing was worse than to be an American.  Evidence of this can be seen in conflicts today as the generation of Muslims brought up on the belief that the U.S. is the constant enemy and must be uprooted from muslim territories has produced an arsenal of ready and willing suicide bombers who give the precious gift of life due to these "framed" beliefs.  And the kids coming up today in America face the challenge of viewing Muslims and Islam free from any negative stereotypes due to current events.  So in closing I think the Soviets were not allowed room to envy another way of life due to the stronghold the regime had on information.
=========yorg=========
